</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JANOME Sewing Machine, the Japanese company entangled in the collapse of a
stock speculator group, reported an after-tax loss of Y24.3bn (Dollars
186.9m) following the liquidation of two affiliates and the restructuring of
its debts.
Strong overseas demand for sewing machines pushed sales for the year 3.4 per
cent higher to Y81.6bn, but pre-tax profit fell 39.3 per cent to Y1.14bn.
Sales for the current year are expected to remain at around Y82bn, with
pre-tax profit forecast to fall to Y500m.
The Janome group is still negotiating with creditors over the fate of
Y235.5bn in debt inherited through its dealings with Koshin, the stock
speculator group, and Nanatomi, a property developer, both of which have
collapsed in the past two years.
Janome, the second largest Japanese sewing machine maker, has received
several managers from Kyowa Saitama Bank, which has been negotiating with
the manufacturer's other creditors in an attempt to buy time on the
repayment of outstanding debt.
Janome is expected to sell some of its extensive land holdings, though it is
keen to delay the sales until a recovery in the weak property market.
