<TEXT>
MALAYSIAN Airline System (MAS) yesterday unveiled a 42 per cent slide in
group pre-tax profit in the year to end-March, AP-DJ reports. MAS also
proposed a rights share issue to raise MDollars 1.75bn (USDollars 694.4m).
Pre-tax profits declined to MDollars 120m from MDollars 206m the previous
year, on revenues ahead to MDollars 3.57bn from MDollars 2.91bn, a rise of
23 per cent.
MAS, whose interim earnings had rebounded from the depressed levels
following the Gulf war, slumped into a MDollars 28.7m operating loss in the
second half of the most recent financial year.
MAS attributed its weak performance to slower-than-anticipated growth in
demand; higher provisions for wage increases; and lower income from aircraft
sales.
The carrier's overall load factor, representing the utilisation of aircraft,
fell 3 percentage points from last year to 65.9 per cent, its lowest level
since 65.1 per cent in 1983.
The load factor's decline is unsettling for analysts because the airline is
pushing ahead with an expanded fleet acquisition programme, under which MAS
plans to buy 72 aircraft in the next five years.
The MDollars 1.75bn rights issue would partly finance the acquisition of 25
new aircraft in this financial year.
