<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / International Company News: Doing business grandfather's way
 -Spain's March family reviewing its investments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The March family, one of the wealthiest in Spain, sits down every 15 to 20
years to think about where it is and where it is going.
As its latest strategic review draws to a close, the family has announced
the sale of Banco de Progreso, its merchant bank subsidiary. The disposal
will bring the family's war chest for new investments up to more than
Pta70bn (Dollars 687m).
Some hurdles remain on the way to the rich new pastures the March clan is
seeking. The family is still stuck with Uralita, a loss-making industrial
holding. It also has to mould Banco Urquijo, a middle-sized and unexciting
retail bank that it owns, into the vehicle for corporate business that
Progreso has become.
The present minders of the family fortune are the brothers Juan and Carlos
March, the grandchildren of the legendary Juan March, who gave financial
backing to General Franco in the Spanish Civil War. The brothers refer
constantly to 'the way grandfather did things'.
'Grandfather' taught them the value of having money in their pockets, which
means they remain traders of companies rather than long-term, committed
investors. They make a distinction between 'real' cash-flow, meaning money
they can walk away with, and 'false' cash-flow, funds that are locked into
an asset. The value of diversification to spread the risk was another lesson
he taught them.
The sale of Progreso to the Barcelona savings bank, La Caixa - in which it
will buy the 70 per cent the family owns and launch a formal takeover for
the rest - will raise the family some Pta12bn.
There was a similar return three months ago when it disposed of a 15.5 per
cent stake in Signet Corporation, its financial arm in the US. Further
boosting the war chest this year, the family has sold an electricity utility
to Endesa, the state-run power group, for Pta40bn, and it has realised a
further Pta14bn with the sale of its interests in the San Miguel brewery to
the French BSN group.
The scale of the disposal programme is equivalent to the one undertaken by
the two brothers in the mid-1970s. Well-schooled by their grandfather to run
the family empire following the early death of their father, Juan and Carlos
March then pulled out of capital-intensive industries, including nuclear
power stations, and sold Transmediterranea, a large shipping firm.
Because they were able to skip so nimbly in front of other investors and
ahead of recession in the 1970s the brothers' new strategy for the 1990s is
being watched closely by would-be peers in Spain.
There are, however, no real surprises in the investments being eyed. The
four main sectors are distribution, communications, environment -
specifically waste management - and leisure. These are exactly the targets
that Spain's large banking and industrial conglomerates, such as Banco
Bilbao Vizcaya and Banesto, have within their sights.
Where the March group scores, in addition to its 'real' cash-flow and its
tight family ethos, is that it is already well-positioned in these sectors.
Two months ago, using Corporacion Alba, the publicly-quoted holding that it
controls, the family partnered the French Carrefour corporation in a Pta25bn
capital increase for Pryca, a large domestic distribution chain that the
March group set up with Carrefour on the back of the 1970s disposals. The
brothers also intend to increase the family's 15 per cent stake in Canal
Plus, a subscriber television network which they view as a magnificent
business.
The environment and leisure interest are at present centred on the
Mediterranean island of Mallorca, the birthplace of grandfather Juan March
and the home of Banca March, a small banking subsidiary that the brothers
term their only 'sentimental asset'.
The family could increase its minority partnership in a hotel interest that
controls 10,000 beds on the island, and they are bidding for waste disposal
concessions that will keep the waters clean and the tourists coming.
The main thorn in the brothers' side is Uralita, the family-controlled
construction and chemical group which began to haemorrhage badly last year
when its posted losses of Pta521m against 1990 profits of Pta5.9bn.
Uralita, which has been badly hit by the reduced earnings of its PVC
manufacturer, Aiscondel, is the sort of business that the brothers
increasingly dislike. They get nervous about cyclical losses that cannot be
blamed on management and they are averse to 'false', or locked-in,
cash-flows.
Unfortunately for the brothers, potential buyers of their industrial holding
are likely to feel the same way.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
