FT  29 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Betacom finance plan could leave Amstrad
with 72% stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMSTRAD, which has interests in computers and satellite dishes, is poised to
take up to 72 per cent of Betacom, the telecommunications equipment
distributor.
Betacom, which is currently trading at a loss, is raising Pounds 8.4m by way
of a share subscription by Amstrad and a rights issue aimed at strengthening
its equity base.
Amstrad is subscribing for 23.95m new ordinary shares in Betacom at 18p per
share. In addition, the rights issue of 23.37m new ordinary shares on a 3
for 4 basis at 18p per share is fully underwritten by Amstrad.
Betacom's shares closed  1/2 p higher yesterday at 18 1/2 p.
Betacom has recently experienced deteriorating trading conditions, lower
sales and higher customer returns. Last year it reported a reduced loss of
Pounds 515,000 (Pounds 2.44m) on sales of Pounds 19.3m (Pounds 18.3m).
Under its current financial circumstances its bank has refused to continue
its support without a significant equity injection.
Amstrad has recently been moving into the telecommunications equipment
business and has announced its intention to market videophones. It took at
29.5 per cent stake in Betacom in February.
It said that rather than see its investment in Betacom acquired for Pounds
1.6m, it had decided to support Betacom's capital increase.
Depending on the outcome of the rights issue, Amstrad could end up with 72
per cent of Betacom's enlarged capital. Its total investment in the company
would amount to Pounds 10.1m.
Furthermore, if the rights issue flops Amstrad, the directors and other
shareholders currently holding over 5 per cent of the company could end up
with in excess of 75 per cent of Betacom, which would lead it to be in
breach of the Stock Exchange's listing requirement that a minimum of 25 per
cent of a company's share capital should be in public hands.
