<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is a growing trend towards getting the public to provide its own
entertainment on television. After those ghastly video clip programmes, full
of embarrassing incidents at weddings, and accident prone toddlers, BBC1 is
offering Joker In The Pack (8.30). 'Ordinary people' tell their favourite
jokes and then, in many cases, collapse in hysterical appreciation of their
own wit. Samples: What's orange and sounds like a parrot? A carrot. A ship
carrying red paint collided with a ship carrying blue paint; both crews were
marooned. You have been warned. However, Rory Bremner (9.00 BBC2) is the
real thing. Some impressionists are either limited in the people they can
'do' or mean with their material. Bremner is profligate. Last week in rapid
succession he did John Major, Barry Norman, Bruce Forsyth, Ted Lowe, John
Smith, Jeremy Paxman, George Bush, Nick Ross, Melvyn Bragg, Donald Sinden,
Douglas Hurd, Peter Snow, Enoch Powell. . .and more. And his jokes are good.
Alien is a space movie about a rocket ship with a hostile life form on
board, directed by Ridley Scott who started off with all those lyrical Hovis
commercials (10.40 ITV).
</TEXT>
