<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Foreign Exchange (10): Poland sets the pattern -
Eastern Europe's move towards convertible currencies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN exchange trading in the former communist world from the Elbe to the
Pacific Ocean used to be either a state-controlled rip-off or a furtive,
back-street affair with money changers who were often secret policemen in
disguise.
The Poles were the most blatant and competitive of black-market dealers and
it was entirely appropriate therefore that Poland became the first of the
post-communist regimes to make its currency, the zloty, internally
convertible and turn foreign exchange dealing over to the private sector.
Poland's trail-blazing liberalisation of its foreign exchange market was an
essential element in the IMF-backed economic stabilisation programme which
began on January 1, 1990. Backed by a Dollars 1bn currency stabilisation
fund provided by western governments and financial institutions the exchange
rate of the zloty was fixed at 9,500 to the dollar, the rate at which it was
trading on the black market.
To general surprise the once-despised socialist currency then appreciated in
real terms for the next 17 months as the internal purchasing power of the
zloty was eroded by inflation while its external value remained fixed. Then
came the first devaluation in May last year followed by introduction of a
crawling peg system which devalues the currency by around 1.8 per cent a
month.
While the central bank maintains this controlled floating regime, actual
trading is carried out in thousands of privately-owned exchange booths and
commercial bank counters equipped with real-time computer terminals which
compete fiercely over their spreads to attract custom.
The success of Poland's bold experiment in foreign exchangeliberalisation
and internal convertibility was followed in a quieter way by several other
former Soviet satellites. In no case, however, has full convertibility been
introduced, involving capital account transactions and non-residents.
Hungary also comes close to full convertibility in practice, however, with
non-residents guaranteed the right to repatriate Forint earnings on direct
and portfolio investments. But even Hungary maintains token limitations on
residents obtaining foreign currency for business or travel purposes and it
remains far easier to change hard currency into local currencies than vice
versa.
The introduction of varying degrees of internal convertibility throughout
eastern and central Europe has been accompanied by the collapse of trade
denominated in the now-defunct transferable rouble and a sharp rise in trade
with hard currency markets. This has led to a corresponding increase in
export-import financing and foreign exchange trading volume.
Between the last quarter of 1989, which saw the destruction of the Berlin
Wall, and the end of the second quarter of 1991 the three central European
countries, Poland, Czechoslovakia and Hungary, which are now associate
members of the European Community, saw their exports to the OECD area rise
by between 13 and 35 per cent, with a corresponding rise in foreign exchange
transactions.
But the most important development in foreign exchange trading is due on
July 1 when the Russian government takes the first big step towards
introducing convertibility for the rouble.
For decades the act of even taking rouble banknotes out of the Soviet Union
was considered a serious criminal offence. Tourists and businessmen alike
were only allowed to change money at a grotesquely over-valued rate while
the gigantic bureaucracies which dealt with foreign trade were tied up in
knots by an incredibly complex structure of foreign trade co-efficients and
other bureaucratic nonsense.
This created a thicket of differing exchange rates which bore no
relationship at all to any concept of market value and made it impossible
for the Soviet authorities to have any rational foreign trade policy.
On July 1, all these various artificial exchange rates will be abolished and
replaced by a single, albeit floating, rate of exchange. The idea is for the
rouble to float for a few months to get an idea of its approximate market
value and then to fix a central rate within a 7.5 per cent fluctuation band.
This is expected 'sometime this autumn', according to Mr Georgy Matiukhin,
the chairman of the Russian central bank.
A huge amount of work remains to be done to train the necessary staff and
set up the infrastructure required to ensure orderly foreign exchange
trading across this huge country extending over nine time zones from St
Petersburg in the west to Sakhalin or Vladivostok in the east, with key oil-
and gas-producing, and therefore hard-currency-earning, Siberia in the
middle.
The new convertible rouble will be the currency of Russia, the largest, and
potentially the richest, of the 15 former Soviet republics which made up the
defunct Soviet Union . Those of the former Soviet republics who want to
remain within the 'rouble zone' will have to play by the rules hammered out
in the inter-republican central bankers' commission where Russia, with its
huge energy and raw material resources, has the most influential voice.
Russia's pre-eminence will be reinforced by the imminent steep rise in the
rouble price of its energy and raw material exports to the other former
Soviet republics. Those republics, like the Baltic states and Ukraine, which
have no oil or gas of their own, will inevitably run up deficits with
Russia. But Moscow's willingness to supply the necessary rouble credits will
depend on the willingness of other republics to play by the new monetary
rules which will accompany rouble convertibility.
As the terms of trade move sharply in Russia's favour the other republics
will have to step up exports to Russia and agree to tight monetary and other
disciplines. In this way, Russia will almost certainly re-assert its
hegemony over the former Soviet republics and enforce economic
re-integration of the rouble zone through a combination of higher energy
prices and convertibility.
If this prognosis is correct the prospect of the former Soviet republics
being able to introduce their own national currencies will be much reduced.
Latvia was the first to introduce its own parallel currency in a move which
the IMF described as 'economic suicide'. The other Baltic states, Estonia
and Lithuania, have similar plans alongside the Ukraine which initially
created a semi-Ukrainian currency by sticking coupons on existing rouble
banknotes. This was essentially part of a rationing system to give nationals
priority access to scarce food and other items, but plans are advanced for
the introduction of the Hryvnia as a fully-fledged national currency.
But the introduction of new currencies is shrouded in considerable
controversy. Mr Matiukhin, diplomatically commented that in the beginning at
least, the new currencies are likely to be as independent as the Scottish
pounds, issued by several Scottish banks, but only under strict Bank of
England control.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
