<DOCNO>FT922-5763</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAAUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Foreign Exchange (6): The Square Mile stays out in
front / Discussing London's role as a leading financial centre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CITY of London has long been proud, if not cocksure, of its reputation
as a leading foreign exchange trading centre.
Brochures published by the Corporation of London boast that London's Square
Mile can still claim to be the world's leading international financial
centre.
But political and financial developments in Europe alongside Britain's
general antipathy towards monetary union have led some to suggest that
London's continuing dominance in foreign exchange trading is in question.
The main concerns over London losing its competitive edge are that the
European Central Bank will be located in another European city and that the
British government will continue to be hostile towards monetary union.
On closer examination, both concerns appear overblown. The Bank of England,
anyway not yet resigned to the ECB going elsewhere, brushes off suggestions
that London's dominant role in global foreign exchange trading would be
weakened if another city were chosen to house the ECB.
The Bank says London's underlying advantages will continue to give the City
an edge over other European centres.
After all, where the bank is located is less important than where it
operates. In the US, the Federal Reserve is based in Washington, but
operates mainly through the largest, most developed and highly securitised
market - New York. The same would surely be true of Europe.
According to the most recent survey of foreign exchange market activity
carried out by the Bank of International Settlements in 1989, the City is
only just behind Tokyo in total international banking business.
In foreign exchange trading, the UK ranked first, with total daily foreign
exchange transactions amounting to Dollars 187bn. This compared with
turnovers of Dollars 129bn in New York and Dollars 115bn in Tokyo. In
Europe, leaving aside London, only Zurich recorded a turnover of more than
Dollars 50bn.
On this basis, the Corporation of London says it is 'hardly surprising' that
'foreign banks have flocked to London, providing the essential cement to the
international flavour of the City'.
There are more than 500 foreign bank branches, incorporations or
representative offices based in London's square mile. Perhaps the most
prestigious of all is the latest international recruit, the headquarters of
the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, with shareholders from
more than 40 countries.
Although the Bank of England believes the City would weather the location of
Europe's central bank outside the UK, it continues to argue strongly that it
should come to London.
In a speech earlier this year, Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the
Bank of England, said it would be in the interests of the European Community
to have its central bank placed in London.
'A single European currency would be one of the world's three major
currencies, and would obviously be actively traded in centres around the
world . . . London is one of the three major world financial centres,
perhaps the only truly international centre and certainly the pre-eminent
international centre in Europe, with a depth, variety and liquidity in its
money and capital markets - which very much now embrace and are developing
the Ecu - that will be vital to an effective single monetary policy,' he
said.
If the ECB does go to one of the so-called 'compromise' candidates, the
'Domesday' scenario is that much of London's foreign exchange trade will go
with it.
'Much depends on what the European Central Bank actually does,' says Ruth
Lea chief economist at Mitsubishi bank in London. 'Will it be just for
committee meetings, or will it be a major operating unit?'
Whatever its role, she dismisses the worst-case scenario; 'I think London
will remain the biggest centre in Europe but it will inevitably lose an edge
if the ECB goes elsewhere.'
Mr Gerard Lyons, chief economist at DKB International, says the Japanese
bank is similarly unflustered at the prospect of London's future.
'There are enough reasons to be positive about London's role - liquidity is
the key factor and London already has that plus a lot of expertise in
foreign exchange. Its infrastructure as an international financial centre
has already been proven,' says Mr Lyons.
However, he cautions that even with these in-built advantages, the location
of the ECB is still important and could yet affect London's position.
'If the ECB is based in a city which clearly doesn't have the potential to
become the European financial centre, like Amsterdam for example, then there
will be no threat to London, but if it goes to Frankfurt, which does have
the potential, then that could pose some sort of problem.'
As for Britain's antipathy towards monetary union, few in the City feel that
London's position in foreign exchange trading would be put in jeopardy if
Britain were to opt out of Emu.
'An awful lot of London's business is offshore business,' said a spokesman
from the Bank of England. 'Because it is an offshore centre, there is every
reason to believe it will continue to be one even if we were not in Emu.'
There is also growing scepticism over the timetable for Emu set out in the
Maastricht treaty. Many in the City view it as unrealistic, and are
confident that no big financial houses would even consider making a move
elsewhere in Europe while the future of monetary union looks so uncertain.
In fact, worries over the attitude of the British government towards Europe
are likely, at least for the time being, to be outweighed by the more
comforting prospect of five years of political stability following the
decisive victory of the Conservative party in the April general election,
especially when compared with the relatively turbulent political outlook
elsewhere in Europe.
Other reasons tying financial houses to London are the exceedingly high
costs now sunk into London. It would take some good reasons indeed for a
company to undertake the enormous cost of relocating its European base.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
