<DOCNO>FT922-5764</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAATFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Foreign Exchange (7): Risk-taking is his business
 -Profile of Julian Simmonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TUESDAY, mid-morning; Citibank's London foreign exchange dealing room is
humming. Smart, young traders bark instructions to each other from opposite
sides of the room, others gaze at flickering green screens, pensively
twirling their telephone handsets.
Presiding over the hubbub from a dealing post bang in the middle of the
spot-desk, is Mr Julian Simmonds, Citibank's energetic managing director of
foreign exchange and money markets in Europe.
After almost 20 years in foreign exchange trading and sales, Mr Simmonds
still approaches his job with the zeal of a newcomer.
'At the end of the day, I actually enjoy my job and I enjoy the people I
work with. If I didn't, I wouldn't bother to get up in the mornings,' he
says.
Responsible for all of Citibank's foreign exchange and funding activities in
Europe, Mr Simmonds' presence in the dealing room and the fact that he
continues to take a position on currencies, is testimony to his love of
risk-taking and ability to avoid, as far as possible, the administrative
side of management.
'Like any other large organisation there is a real risk at senior levels of
management of getting dragged away from your desk,' he says. 'One of my key
challenges is to not allow myself to become engulfed in a sea of papers and
meetings. You can't watch the market if you are stuck in meetings.'
The approach means that he can stay in touch with his workforce and with
Citibank's customers. Understanding customers' needs has become a key part
of Simmonds' approach to forex trading.
'I don't believe the business of banking is any different from other service
industries,' says Mr Simmonds. 'The product we are trying to sell is foreign
exchange. I approach the challenge by thinking, what is it I want when I go
into a mojor store to make a big acquisition?'
One initiative has been to survey customers' needs through a questionnaire.
Mr Simmonds reads every single return, tackling weak areas directly with the
sales, trading and administrative teams.
All this makes him a busy man. He is into the office by 7.45am and tries to
be home by 6.15pm. When away from his desk, he regularly glances at a
portable Reuters screen that he carries with him everywhere. At night he is
frequently woken by traders keeping him in touch with his position.
Two things help - he claims not to need much sleep and he has an
understanding wife.
Certainly Mr Simmonds, a vigorous 41, shows no sign of the 'burn-out' often
associated with the frantic life of forex risk-takers.
'Burn-out comes from excessive alcohol and entertainment, not from the
work,' he says. 'I am only prepared to entertain in the evenings where it is
important, and wherever possible I try to involve my wife.'
Family life is important. 'When the kids tell me about their latest crisis
at school, it puts the job in perspective.'
The only downside of the job to which Mr Simmonds is devoted, he says, is
failure. 'But it's a risk business, and failing is something you have to
learn to live with.
'You have to do what you think best in the business. If I buy dollars
because I think the dollar is going up, and I make a mistake, then I can
live with it. I am disappointed, but I can live with it,' he says.
</TEXT>
