<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Foreign Exchange (3): Stability amid turmoil - Yen
shrugs off changes in the Japanese economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOMESTIC financial and political turmoil and far-reaching global political
change have left the yen remarkably unscathed over the past year.
In the fiscal year 1991, the dollar averaged Y133, with the currency moving
in a range of Y15, the second smallest fluctuation since it floated against
the dollar in 1973. The currency has shrugged off significant changes
affecting the Japanese economy such as long-bond yields falling from last
year's 9 per cent to the recent 5.2 per cent, and the stock market down more
than 55 per cent from its peak. The stock market scandals and political
bribery allegations that shook Japan last year failed to rock the yen.
The authorities have shown that they are able to stabilise currency markets.
Earlier this year, the Bank of Japan and Federal Reserve Bank of New York
were selling dollars in co-ordinated intervention. According to Mr Paul
Summerville, economist at Jardine Flemings in Tokyo, increased information
has also decreased currency fluctuation. 'Dollar/yen movements are becoming
limited because information is discounted into the rate every day,' he says.
However, the middle- and long-term trend in supply and demand points to a
strengthening of the yen. Japan's current account surplus for the fiscal
year to March 1991 surged by 167 per cent from the previous year to Dollars
90bn. Official figures disclosed a record surplus of Dollars 113bn in the
trade account, and a surplus of Dollars 40bn in the long-term capital
account, the first surplus since 1980.
The long-term capital account surplus followed a sharp increase to Dollars
101bn in foreign net purchases of Japanese securities from Dollars 60bn.
Foreigners bought a net Dollars 36.77bn in Japanese stocks, up from Dollars
15.92bn in fiscal 1990.
Japanese investment in overseas markets has started to shrink, as excess
liquidity has been squeezed out, and overseas and domestic interest rate
differentials have narrowed. In 1991, Japanese direct investment was Dollars
23.6bn, down from Dollars 44.9bn, reflecting tougher financial conditions at
home and the world recession.
Long-term capital flows are expected to remain in surplus for Japan as
Japanese investors continue to favour domestic investments and foreigners
remain net buyers of Japanese equities, prompting Mr Robert Feldman, an
economist at Salomon Brothers in Tokyo, to forecast that the yen will
strengthen to Y115 against the dollar.
In addition to payments surpluses, Mr Masao Susaki, head of research at the
Bank of Tokyo, says that dollar/yen forward contracts affect the currency
rate.
'Japanese exporters and speculators made positions in dollar selling forward
contracts in the late 80s and have been rolling the positions over,' says Mr
Susaki.
He says investors and exporters will start selling the dollar against the
yen from mid-1992. Mr Susaki expects the average dollar/yen rate to be
around Y123 this fiscal year.
Mr Hideki Furuya, senior economist at Sanwa Research Institute, says that
economic fundamentals dominate the yen currency movements, and political and
financial scandals tend to be secondary factors in the long run.
Mr Furuya says that while the yen has weakened on the back of a slowing
Japanese economy, recent economic figures indicate a gradual recovery. After
declines in industrial production, inventory growth has slowed to a 7 per
cent increase in March, down from a peak 13 per cent in December.
Housing demand is showing signs of a recovery, reflecting the fall in
interest rates on housing loans. The economy is also expected to benefit
from the government's stimulatory package, which brings forward 75 per cent
of this fiscal year's public works spending into the first half. According
to Mr Furuya, this will have the same impact as an increase of Y3,000bn in
spending.
Reflecting the gradual recovery of the economy and a rise in long-term
interest rates towards the end of the year, Mr Furuya forecasts the yen will
rise to Y125.
Mr Summerville, at Jardine Fleming, sees the D-Mark/yen rate averaging
between Y70 and Y75 in fiscal year 1992.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
