<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAAOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Foreign Exchange (1):  Caught in the eye of a
storm - Leading currencies have been buffeted by world upheavals over the
past 18 months. A symptom of a recent uneasy calm has been a marked decline
in the volatility of the so-called G3 exchange rates - the dollar, D-Mark
and yen / Assessment of the future of currency markets in the light of
economic and political events
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORLD'S foreign exchange markets are caught in the eye of a storm.
Leading currencies are suspended between geo-political pressures for change
on the one hand and, on the other hand, institutional developments in the
global banking industry and moves to greater integration in western Europe
which argue for calm.
A symptom of this unstable equilibrium has been a marked decline this year
in the volatility of the so-called G3 exchange rates - the dollar, D-Mark
and yen.
The dollar's fluctuation range against the D-Mark in the first 4 1/2 months
of this year was just 18 pfennigs as it moved between a low of DM1.50 and a
high of DM1.68. This, according to Swiss Bank Corp, is less than half last
year's trading range of 39 pfennigs and well below the 105 pfennig trading
range recorded in 1985, when market conditions were especially turbulent.
The movement of the dollar against the yen has been even more subdued - a
mere 12 yen between a low of Y123 and a high of Y135, against fluctuation
ranges of Y19 last year, Y35 in 1990, Y51.5 in 1986 and Y63 in 1985.
The decline in exchange rate volatility has reflected a number of forces in
the world economy and banking industry since the mid-1980s.
Governments want more stable exchange rates. Although the Group of Seven
countries - the US, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada - no
longer attempt to peg their exchange rates to each other as after the 1987
Louvre Accord, they act when necessary to combat excessive exchange rate
movements.
More important perhaps have been regional developments. In particular, the
exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System has increasingly
taken on the characteristics of a fixed exchange rate block. It has
attracted new members (Spain, Britain and Portugal over the past three
years) and acts as a centre of gravity for non-EC countries such as Sweden,
Norway and Finland which peg their currencies to the European currency unit
(Ecu) and are seeking closer links to the EMS. ERM rigidity has grown with
the adoption last December at the EC's Maastricht summit of plans to move to
Emu, or economic and monetary union, by the end of the decade.
All industrialised nations put a high priority on combatting inflation.
While there has been increased recognition that national economic policy
measures must vary to take account of differing conditions, convergence
towards low inflation has helped iron out one classic cause of exchange rate
movement.
Central banks have become more adept at managing intervention. They no
longer defend specific currency rates, preferring instead to carry out
smoothing operations in the exchange markets. These more refined tactics
have deprived speculators of the 'one-way bet' that so often appeared when
fixed or semi-fixed rates were defended, only to be abandoned under the
pressure of speculative forces.
These trends have been reinforced by developments in banking and among other
market participants.
In general, the currency markets have become more risk averse. Caution has
grown with the approach of the end-1992 deadline for international banks to
comply with stringent capital adequacy ratios, agreed in 1988. Loan losses
incurred during the past three years of slow growth and recession have
curbed banks' enthusiasm for speculative foreign exchange trading.
But it would be wrong to assume that calm will endure in the foreign
exchange markets. Following the collapse of communism and the end of the
Cold War, the currency markets, like policy makers, are operating in a world
where old certainties no longer hold good.
The strength of the US economic recovery is unclear, as is the capacity of
Germany to absorb the new eastern Lander without allowing inflation to run
out of control. There are doubts whether the authorities in Tokyo will be
able to stave off recession while managing the current problem of asset
price deflation in Japan. Overshadowing these worries, is the unfathomable
outlook for the republics of the former Soviet Union as they embark along
the road to the market economy.
Large-scale changes in exchange rate relationships may emerge once there are
answers to these uncertainties. When determining exchange rates, the market
has already begun to look much more closely at underlying economic and
political factors than simply at nominal interest rate differentials or the
trend lines drawn by chartists.
Such considerations lie behind the late spring reappraisal of sterling and
the French franc, which has allowed the authorities in London and Paris to
bring their official interest rates almost down to German levels.
The dollar's reaction to last December's interest rate changes in Germany
and the US, when Germany pushed its rates to their highest peace-time levels
since the 1930s and the US responded by cutting its discount rate to the
lowest level for nearly a generation, provided an early example of this
trend.
After an initial downwards move, the dollar responded to the yawning 6
percentage-point interest differential in favour of the D-Mark by moving
higher. Investors in this case looked beyond the immediate horizon and
reasoned that the news was good for the US economy. They also assumed
(wrongly as it happened) that the next move in dollar interest rates would
be upwards.
While fast-moving economic and political changes make smooth running
currency markets more important than ever, the general decline in exchange
rate volatility has been bad for profits.
These factors have reinforced a tendency for trading in the leading
currencies to become concentrated among a small number of big,
well-capitalised players such as Citibank and Chemical Bank of the US, Union
Bank of Switzerland and Barclays Bank of Britain.
Trading in leading currencies takes place in a mature market, where
information is very rapidly disseminated to all participants and competitive
edge is hard to achieve. A strong customer base has become all important,
not just for the business that it brings but for the insight it provides on
exchange rates movements. As capital flows have supplanted trade flows as
the engine of market activity, traders have had to develop more
sophisticated services such as options and derivatives to win business from
institutional clients.
In this very competitive environment it seems that London has continued to
build up its position as the world's leading foreign exchange centre, at the
expense of Tokyo, where Japanese banks have been hard hit by the asset price
fall, and New York, where a lack of liquidity, particularly on Fridays, has
forced some foreign exchange banks there to function as niche players.
But such concentration of muscle does not mean an absence of business
opportunities elsewhere. Markets for so-called exotic currencies, from
eastern Asia or Latin America, are becoming more prominent.
They offer opportunities for smaller trading companies to operate on their
own account and provide some of the excitement that used to characterise the
foreign exchange market as a whole in the 1970s and 1980s.
In a business that sometimes wonders whether it is in decline, trading in
second line currencies will continue to grow.
The historic currencies of western Europe may be destined to disappear if
plans for Emu are fulfilled. But other currencies will gain importance as
the ex-communist countries of eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union
embrace the market economy and move towards currency convertibility.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page I
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-5770</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAANFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Coventry (11): Labour-dominated scene - Economic
successes for moderates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR Party was returned with ease as the largest party in the recent
local elections for the Coventry city council.
In April, Mr Dave Nellist, who was expelled last year from the Labour Party,
ran as an independent and this factor tended to dominate coverage of the
general election for Coventry.
These two developments may have created the impression that - seen from a
distance - Coventry was a little like Liverpool: an industrial,
predominantly working class city, faced with a struggle between the hard
left and Labour Party moderates.
In the event, Mr Dave Nellist, a popular local man who had built up a
reputation as a good constituency member of parliament, was defeated in
Coventry South East by the official Labour Party candidate, Mr Jim
Cunningham.
But it was a close-run thing - Mr Cunningham polled 11,902; Mr Nellist,
Independent Labour, 10,551; while Mrs Martine Hyams polled 10,591 for the
Conservatives - showing a seven per cent swing to the Tories from Labour
since the 1987 election.
At a local level, however, any faction-fighting within the Labour Party was
not a consideration. The Conservatives did gain five seats at the expense of
the Labour Party, but Labour still held an overwhelming 41 seats, with none
going to the Liberal Democrats.
Mr Bob Ainsworth, who won the Coventry North East seat for the Labour party
says: 'The hard left or extreme left - or whatever you would like to call it
 -has never had much influence at a local level.'
The Labour city council is widely seen as united and moderate council which
has been the main driving force behind the successful diversification of the
economy. Mr Jim Cunningham the new MP for Coventry South East, who was the
leader of the council until his election, says: 'We realised in 1981 we had
to change. We had to broaden the base from the car industry. The alternative
was mass unemployment. We built the science park with the university; we
took the initiative in building Westwood Park - Barclays Bank has moved to
Westwood. If Barclays bank is prepared to move to Coventry, then it must be
confident of the City's future.'
Mr Cunningham says there was little opposition from within the Labour Party
to these entrepreneurial policies - 'the only people to oppose us were the
Conservatives. The government didn't like the idea of local authorities
building science parks - they didn't like the idea of any public authority
spending money on that kind of thing.'
Mr Bob Ainsworth (Coventry North East) who is a former deputy leader of the
city council says: 'We were able to get things moving in the early 1980s
because - abnormally for a city council - we had a lot of assets.
'We owned most of the city centre and we had a lot of land. We were able to
use this land to enter into deals with developers. It's a lot more difficult
now, of course, because any land sales have to go mostly towards debt
relief.'
Asked whether the disturbances in the estate of Wood End in mid-May are not
worrying and harmful for the image of a city still trying to attract new
investment, Mr Cunningham says: 'Of course they are worrying - but it isn't
just Coventry, is it? All the talk I have been hearing in the House of
Commons is where is it going to be next.
'The basic problem in the inner cities is the young unemployed; many, in
their late 20s, and without jobs, feel disenfranchised and let down. It
isn't an ethnic problem, as has been suggested - the minorities are as badly
affected as everyone else.
'The trouble is there isn't enough training: anyone connected with the Tec
(Training and Enterprise Council) will tell you there are not enough funds.'
Mr Ainsworth, who made his maiden speech on the subject of the Coventry
disturbances, says: 'This kind of thing is going to happen until we have a
proper urban policy. Unemployment in these estates is so very high and many
people are unemployed for so long that it's socially acceptable not to work.
These people are without a stake in society.'
He continues: 'The tabloid press has exaggerated the disturbances - the
police never lost control of the estate. There were not great numbers
involved.
'The damage to property was not extensive. But yes, if the exaggeration is
believed, then it could harm Coventry's attempts to attract new companies.'
Mr John Butcher, a former government minister, the MP for Coventry South
West and the only Conservative among Coventry's four MPs, agrees that the
Labour-dominated council has done a good job in diversifying the economy: 'I
would say that there has been a healthy partnership between the local
authority, the educational bodies and the government.
'Now, of course, development of science parks and industrial estates will be
more and more in the hands of the private sector.'
In regard to disturbances Mr Butcher says: 'It has nothing to do with race,
as has been suggested. The problem here is a few young people, known to the
police, who decided to go on the rampage. The police have the situation
under control.
'The encouraging thing is that older people on the estate want to see the
young offenders dealt with. It is wrong to conclude from these events that
Coventry has a law and order problem.'
</TEXT>
