<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAAIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Coventry (9): The roots go deep - Peugeot Talbot's
community involvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW MACLEOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FEW weeks ago, a small community group in the Stoke area of Coventry
needed access to a photocopying machine, to duplicate a newsletter. It
turned for help to an unexpected quarter.
In many areas the appeal would automatically have been made to the local
authority, or one of its agencies. In Stoke, however, as in many other parts
of the city, it is increasingly Peugeot Talbot, the French car manufacturer
 -the antecedents of which put down roots in the fabric of Coventry early
this century - where such requests are heard.
Roots - or Rootes - is the operative word, of course. Lord Rootes, as he
later became, was one of the men who helped found the city's wealth on the
motor car, and having prospered so much from the skills and hard work of the
local people, he resolved to put something back.
Perhaps the most public evidence of Rootes patronage in the city is the
widely-respected University of Warwick, which despite its name is well
within the city boundary, and which came into being thanks largely to the
family's influence.
Peugeot Talbot assumed the role of patron when it acquired the ailing UK
business of Chrysler, which had absorbed Rootes Group some years earlier. Mr
Dick Parham, the deputy managing director, concedes that the company's
charitable efforts were permitted to wane in the years following the
takeover, as the management wrestled with the more pressing problems of
survival.
Some four years ago there was a sea change in Peugeot Talbot's fortunes, and
it became obvious that the company was riding the crest of a wave. At about
the same time, Mr Geoffrey Whalen, the managing director, and his board
members looked again at the company's place in the community. Mr Parham
deliberately chooses small instances, like the offer to duplicate the
newsletter, to illustrate Peugeot's belief that there is more to community
involvement than cheque book charity - the glamorous and well-publicised
business of allocating large sums for heart-rending causes.
The story can be told in figures, of course - charitable giving last year of
Pounds 181,000, covenants to hospitals, schools and community associations,
lists of cars on long-term loan to deserving organisations. But the
statistics alone leave the true nature of Peugeot's commitment in shadow.
The whole issue is illuminated, and given character, by the people who work
for the company, and who, from the boardroom to the shop-floor, immerse
themselves in local affairs.
SHOP-FLOOR workers are actively encouraged to involve themselves in local
matters. The company, which already supplies four JPs to the local bench,
recently asked for more volunteers to allow their names to go forward.
Coventry's current lord mayor, Mr Dave Edwards, is an employee, as is the
next mayor of Nuneaton, Mr Tony Lloyd.
Among his many activities, Mr Whalen chairs the Coventry and Warwickshire
Training and Enterprise Council, and has ensured that Peugeot Talbot
personnel have been seconded to help with its work. Mr Parham is chairman of
ADEPT - the Agency Developing Enterprise Partnership and Trust - which arose
from the bishops' Faith in the City working party, and concentrates its work
on the less privileged areas of the city. He was also instrumental in
setting up the 'Spirit of Coventry' movement, which has now merged its
interests with the newer, and like-minded, 'Coventry Is Making It' campaign.
Other executives are engaged in similar work throughout the city - the
purchasing director lends his expertise to the Coventry health authority,
and the finance director serves as a governor at Hereward College, the
city's national further education establishment specifically for the
disabled.
Links with education - and a desire to see employees enrich their lives in
and out of the workplace - are strong at the company. The company sponsors
Coventry Polytechnic's business school, helping to strengthen links between
education and industry. It works closely with local schools and offers work
experience to 16-18 year-olds. The firm has built a partnership centre, with
an accent on foreign languages.
Sporting ties are strong. The company sponsors Coventry City, Coventry Rugby
Club, and Warwickshire Cricket Club - giving it a hand in the three most
popular spectator sports in the area. On a broader front, Peugeot last year
launched an assisted learning programme, allocating Pounds 250,000 for any
studies - vocational or otherwise - to which employees are attracted, in the
belief that anything which stimulates the learning habit will eventually
enhance a fast-changing shop floor where the ability to pick up new skills
quickly will be of crucial importance.
By co-incidence, French has so far proved to be the most popular course,
even for workers who do not need it for their jobs. But others have chosen
to earmark their cash from the scheme in the pursuit of HGV licences,
fork-lift truck skills - and even passing the standard driving test.
'We've made rapid progress over the past few years - but we've by no means
finished. We can now give a lead, and harness the desire in the workforce to
help in the community by having this effectively as part of the company's
ethos,' Mr Parham explains.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
