<DOCNO>FT922-5776</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAAHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Coventry (7): The city's largest employer -
Coventry City Council has substantial property holdings
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
COVENTRY City Council has long tentacles. This is not just a matter of the
number of people it employs, or the extent of the services it provides. It
also has substantial property holdings, more and more of which are likely to
become the subject of joint venture developments with the private sector.
At the same time, the Council's position as the city's largest employer
suggests that it is a significant influence on the local labour market. It
is in a position to act as a role model for the private sector, through, for
example, the pursuit of active training policies and the practice of equal
opportunity. Whether such influence will be sustained during a period in
which increasing constraints are being placed on local government
expenditure remains to be seen.
Contrary to the national trend, the size of the Council's employment roll
has actually increased over the last two years, although it is now starting
to drift down. In 1990 the Council had, in the jargon, 12,982 full time
equivalent employees. The latest figure, said Mr John McGuigan, the
assistant chief executive, is about 14,000.
The numbers are up to 300 fewer than a year ago, but, said Mr McGuigan, 'the
progressive reduction has not been as dramatic as other authorities.' This
is largely because Council staff have won contracts for rubbish collection,
housing maintenance and sports and leisure facilities' management that had
been put out to tender. But the total will drop as, for instance, further
education passes away from local authority control and as spending cuts take
effect.
The spending cuts spring from the disparity between what the council wanted
to spend and what the government thought it ought to spend. The government's
standard spending assessment for Coventry for the 1992-93 fiscal year was
Pounds 234.9m, an increase of 5.6 per cent over 1991-92; it was prepared to
allow spending of Pounds 245.3m, but any spending over that second figure
would have resulted in poll tax capping.
The initial City Council spending proposal was Pounds 251.7m. It has thus
had to shave that by Pounds 6.4m to avoid capping and, effectively, the
imposition of a government budget on the city. It came through with Pounds
6.9m of cuts, after an anguished spending survey which put potential council
economies into three categories: those which are politically unacceptable,
those which the Council is unwilling to face but would have to, and those
which it would have thought about doing anyway.
The burden of the cuts fell on the education service - Pounds 5.38m -
followed by personnel and administration, accounting for Pounds 1.24m, and
transportation and highways, accounting for Pounds 1.14m.
The financial position of the Council would have been stronger had it not
lost Pounds 0.5m in property rents, because of the weakness of the property
market and because of the necessity to make provision for failures to
collect the poll tax.
In both these regards, Coventry is not in a markedly different position from
any other council in the UK. In fact, its position on poll tax collection
has been better than most.
Mr McGuigan estimated that about 10 per cent of the city's people had not
paid anything at all. This is a relatively small proportion, given the
political agitation about payment. There was, indeed, a local campaign waged
against poll tax waged by Mr Dave Nellist, the former Labour MP for Coventry
South East who fought the seat - vainly as it turned out - in the general
election as an Independent. The council budget for 1992-93 assumes a six per
cent non-payment rate.
The council, best described as 'pragmatic Labour,' has played the poll tax
issue quietly, as its label might suggest it would. Equally, it is adopting
a pragmatic approach to development, especially where its own landholdings
are concerned.
It has dropped a passive approach of simply responding to private sector
approaches which might be forthcoming on a particular piece of land, or on a
particular social scheme.
Instead, it has been identifying possibilities for development and making it
clear that it is prepared to talk with anybody who is prepared to envisage a
joint venture, the structure of which would have to meet certain broad
criteria. These include long term partnership, as opposed to short term
funding, and a readiness to meet council objectives as well as producing
private sector profits.
Cases in point include the search for a partner to run and develop Coventry
Airport, the rehabilitation of Coombe Abbey and the creation around it of
more leisure facilities (covered in an article on the China Connection; see
facing page), a scheme to generate power from waste incineration, the
enhancement of the area around Coventry Cathedral and the expansion of
business parks around the outside of the city.
Co-operation with the private sector is necessarily an integral part of
Coventry's 1992 City Challenge bid. It is competing with other local
authorities to win government funding of Pounds 37.5m, spread over five
years, to revive the inner city wards of St Michael's and Foleshill.
Within this bid there are three large schemes where private sector companies
will play the major role. British Gas and Carroll Business Parks plan to
reclaim the old Foleshill gas works for a new business park.
Courtaulds and Inner City Enterprises wish to turn a vacant headquarters
building into a centre for the clothing industry and a new enterprise
centre. Ideal Homes and Moorfield envisage new homes and offices on a
derelict part of the Coventry Canal Basin.
For the Council, over and above the question of developing links with the
private sector, the City Challenge bid is of fundamental importance. Its
success or failure could speed or retard plans for revival in the poorest
part of the city.
If the bid is successful there will be an injection of central government
funds. But if it fails there is likely to be less funding for the city from
the government's Urban Programme. This is because the funds allotted to City
Challenge by the government come out of existing budgets. So, more spending
on City Challenge means less spending elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
