<DOCNO>FT922-5778</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAAFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Coventry (5): Cost and access a spur for inward
moves - The National Grid is among companies which have moved their
operations to the Midlands city
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OFFICIALS AT Coventry City Council realised they would have to diversify the
city's economy in the early 1980s. The recession of 1979-81 had been
traumatic for Coventry, with around 53,000 jobs lost by 1982, compared with
the mid-70s. Over this period, the dominant industries - car-making and
related engineering - cut back their activities.
In 1980, 46 per cent of the workforce was employed in manufacturing of some
kind, most of in the automotive industry: it became obvious too that many of
the jobs lost were not going to reappear when the economic cycle turned
favourable.
An economic development unit at the city council was formed in 1986, and
from 1987 different kinds of companies began to move to Coventry.
Equity and law Life Assurance Company had already moved some of its
operations to Coventry in 1974, but the company, had been very much a lone
beacon in the financial services sector. Coventry was seen as a
manufacturing city, with the necessary related services being carried out in
nearby Birmingham.
The absence of a white collar culture meant that very little B1
industrial/office space was available for high technology or financial
services companies. The situation began to change with the founding in 1982
of the University of Warwick Science Park, a 45-acre site owned by the
university and developed jointly by the university and the city council.
Today there are 65 companies, many of them high technology concerns,
employing more than 1,100 people on the park.
Another development, Westwood Business Park, was brought on stream in 1986.
This 100-acre site which is close to the science park provided the
breakthrough the city needed. Again, it was developed by the city council,
but this time in conjunction with private sector developers. It has proved
attractive to financial services companies: Barclays Bank, which now employs
850 people in Coventry, and RSA Examinations Board, which employs 130 people
are two well known service companies which have moved operations to the
park.
The city council estimates that, in all, 157 companies have moved part or
all of their operations to Coventry since 1987, creating 10,570 new jobs.
This has meant that the percentage employed in manufacturing has dropped to
35 per cent.
On the science park, some of the high-technology companies include Sun
Microsystems, Buehler International, Telemecanique and Olivetti.
Other companies which have relocated to Coventry include the National Grid
employing 800 people at a new headquarters building; Midland Bank, which has
established a regional data headquarters, and employs 250 people, the
Department of Transport which has a regional administration unit involved in
motorway widening, and which employs 130 people, and Mortgages plc, a
financial services group, which employs 158.
A successful diversification is thus clearly under way for a variety of
reasons. The city does qualify for some government assistance as an
intermediate development area, but it has not had new town or urban
development status, and has not received large government grants to prime
the pump for developers.
The cheap cost of Coventry has, however, been a factor. In the late 1980s
rents for offices were as low as Pounds 7 a sq ft compared with Pounds 15
for Birmingham. There was also an abundance of skilled labour following
redundancies at car plants. Mr Myles Mackie, the investment and policy
adviser at the city council, feels the accessibility of Coventry has also
been important. He says, 'I know every town looking for investment claims it
is the centre of England, but Coventry really is: we are the closest part of
the Midlands to London - it's only an hour and 20 minutes by train. We're
close to the motorways, but there is good internal access. The ring road
actually works and there is little congestion in the city centre, unlike big
cities, such as Birmingham.'
But also important has been the ability of the local authority to provide
the right kind of accommodation. The RSA Examination Board when it wanted to
move out of London in 1988 appointed agents to find a new site. They found
premises in Nottingham and Derby, but they were unsuitable because they were
on industrial estates next to companies manufacturing. The Board wanted a
clean business-like environment and the Westwood estate fitted the bill.
Costs have risen since the late 1980s, and B1 business premises would now
cost around Pounds 13 a sq ft., but this is still competitive with other
relocation towns such as Milton Keynes, Peterborough and even Telford; 12
other industrial estates apart from the science park and the Westwood
business park are open for business, representing several hundreds of acres
of B1 space.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-5779</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAAEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Coventry (6): Schemes have matured - Youth and
adult training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Coventry and Warwickshire Training and Enterprise Council was set up in
September 1990. This was a difficult moment: it was a time when a key
Coventry employer, Jaguar, was making large numbers redundant.
The TEC has been able to take in some, but by no means all of the 1,000 or
so employees made jobless at Jaguar, under its Employment Training
programme.
The ET scheme, together with the Youth Training Scheme, is one of the two
major programmes which the Coventry and Warwickshire Tec like other Tecs has
inherited from the government's Training Agency.
The ET programme is designed for the older workers, who are thrown on to the
labour market in mid-life and who run the risk without retraining of
becoming long-term unemployed.
YTS was designed for young people between the ages of 16 and 19 with the aim
of giving them vocational qualifications.
The programme for former Jaguar workers is rather special in that Jaguar is
making facilities available for retraining and the Coventry Chamber of
Commerce is also involved along with the Coventry and Warwickshire Tec.
But the TEC has also had to absorb others made jobless in the recent
recession.
Mr Scott Glover, the chief executive of the Tec, says that there are around
3,000 people on the ET programme at any given time. He rejects suggestions
that the ET programme has just become an easy way for long-term unemployed
to pick up money with no real intention of taking a job.
'Seventy five per cent of thepeople we have interviewed, and this includes
employers as well as people on the scheme, have said they feel the scheme
has been very beneficial,' he says. He estimates that there is a successs
rate of 25 per cent of people on the scheme finding new work - 'this is not
high enough of course, but it is early days in the scheme and there has been
a fierce recession.'
Several millions of the budget of Pounds 25m is spent on adult training.
Around 56 per cent of the total goes on youth training which is the other
main programme inherited from the training agency.
The idea is that young people of between 16 and 19 are given funds with
which they can not support themselves exist but also buy some training -
either on-job training or at a college or a combination of both - which will
lead to a recognised national vocational qualification (NVA).
There was much criticism of the youth training scheme (YTS) when it was
administered by the Training Agency.
It was said that some employers 'just used young people as cheap labour' and
failed to give them training. Young people on the other hand saw the YTS as
a government ruse to deny them their social security money or unemployment
benefit, since acceptance of YTS money implied taking a job of some kind
whether it entailed training or not.
Mr Glover says: 'The schemes vary from area to area. But yes, I suppose in
the early days the YTS was designed to get young people off the streets. But
the schemes have matured. They are not known as the youth training schemes,
but just youth training. Our surveys show that 75 per cent of young people
involved in our programmes are receiving training of some kind which should
lead to a vocational qualification.'
The Coventry and Warwickshire Tec has not gone over to the voucher scheme
adopted by other Tecs. Under this system, the young person is given a
voucher or credit which can then be cashed in to buy training. Instead, the
Coventry Tec goes in for what Mr Glover calls 'flexible funding.' This means
giving the young person as much as possible to meet his or her training
needs.
'We must recognise it takes more to train an engineer than it does a
typist,' he says.
Funding remains a problem. There are 310,000 people in Coventry and 480,000
in wider Warwickshire. The Pounds 25m is only a fraction more than the
Training Agency was spending before the Tec was set up.
BESIDES the two training programmes the Tec has also taken over the
enterprise scheme and is responsible for small business.
The Tec wants to to do more than perpetuate old schemes.
The main thrust of its aims is closer targetting. By this is meant surveys
to find out what are the skills needs of the area and a closer involvement
with companies, local authorities, and educational authorities to try and
match those skills with the right kind of training.
One recent survey showed a need for, among other things:
Drivers for heavy goods, fork lift and public service vehicles.
In engineering - craft technicians and engineers.
Tourism, catering and hotel staff.
Management skills of all kinds.
All forms of electricians and electronic engineers.
All modern offices skills, eg computing and word processing.
This survey was taken at a time when unemployment was over 12 per cent in
Coventry although much lower in Warwickshire as a whole. It showed a
considerable skills mismatch.
The economy of Coventry has changed over the past decade with a
diversification into high technology industries away from the dependence on
engineering in the automotive industry.
Nevertheless, the 200 largest companies still employ nearly 40 per cent of
the workforce.
It is expected that some of these companies will shed further labour and
that there will be a high proportion of men and women in their 50s needing
retraining. One scheme which the TEC is behind is to get big companies to
use their facilities to train people from smaller concerns or from business
start-ups.
'This all takes time. We are evolutionary, rather than revolutionary,' says
Mr Glover. He stresses though, that the Tec does not want to be a provider
of training itself but wants to be an enabler or facilitator. This means the
main aim is to get local companies and education bodies involved - and keep
them involved.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
