<DOCNO>FT922-5780</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE2ATAADFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Coventry (4): The shake-out takes its toll -
Manufacturing, the quality as well as the quantity of jobs on offer has
decline / The decline of the manufacturing sector and the rise of the
services sector leads to a mismatch of local skills
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONCE upon a time, when the sun shone on the Coventry economy and never
looked likely to set, city unemployment was about half of one per cent. That
was in 1955. Now, nearly a generation of change later, the contrast is
savage.
Over the last six months, said the West Midlands Enterprise Board in latest
analysis of unemployment in the old West Midlands metropolitan county, 'the
highest rate of increase has been in Coventry where the jobless total has
risen by 13 per cent, and the lowest has been in Birmingham where there has
been a rise of 6.1 per cent. In the county as a whole, there has been a fall
of 0.1 per cent over the last month and a rise of 8.5 per cent over the last
six months.'
Coventry, in other words, has been faring worse in employment terms than
other parts of the West Midlands conurbation. However, within this
generalisation, encapsulated in an overall unemployment rate of 14.1 per
cent against a national average of 9.4 per cent, there are distinct local
and sectoral variations.
Firstly, men have suffered from redundancies to a greater extent than women.
This is not a phenomenon peculiar to Coventry, but as the City Council noted
last year, men were losing their jobs at twice the rate of women, confirming
that 'the current recession is affecting mostly male full-time employment.'
The latest jobless totals have a male unemployment rate of 18.1 per cent and
a female rate of 8.0 per cent.
Secondly, and this follows on from the first point, redundancies appear to
have been taking place at a much higher rate in the manufacturing sector,
where there is the highest incidence of full time male employment, than in
the services sector, where there is a high level of female, part-time
employment.
The list of companies which have announced redundancies in recent months is
full of household names: Alvis, British Coal, closing the last pit in the
area; Courtaulds, Dunlop Aviation, Federal Express, GPT, Massey Ferguson,
Matrix Churchill and so on.
Third, the geographic distribution of unemployment in the city shows that
some wards are markedly more affected than others - 'there is still a strong
north-west/south-east divide,' observes the City Council, 'with much lower
rates evident in the areas to the south and east of the city centre and very
high rates within the inner city wards.'
The worst affected wards are St Michael's and Foleshill, where male jobless
rates run at 34.0 and 29.0 per cent respectively. They are also the wards
where there is the highest concentration of ethnic minorities  - Asian and
Afro-Caribbean. Their male unemployment rate is twice as high as the white
rate, and their female rate is three times higher than the white.
It is these wards where, says Mr Trevor Cornfoot, head of economic
development at the City Council, 'there is a real difficulty of trying to
secure adequate employment.' Partly, he notes, this is because the wards are
among the early industrialised areas of Coventry and over the last two
decades there has been a succession of large factory closures, including
Alfred Herbert, the machine tool manufacturer, and Morris Engines. Not
surprisingly, the two wards are the setting of Coventry's City Challenge bid
for new government urban renewal funding.
The steady rise in unemployment, as the recession has bitten deeper, has
taken place against the background of a decline in the working population,
itself a movement in parallel with a declining population. Official
estimates show that the total population is expected to decline to 296,000
by next year from 326,000 in 1979, while the working population will reduce
to 177,000 by next year from 193,000 in 1979.
But within these declining numbers there has been a perceptible shift in the
nature of employment. The string of manufacturing redundancies of recent
months has simply exacerbated a trend which has been apparent in varying
degrees from the early 1970s: the lower importance of manufacturing and the
higher importance of services in the employment mix. The 1989 employment
census, coming after a decade of deep cuts in capacity, still showed,
however, that 40 per cent of the workforce was employed in manufacturing,
against a national average of 23 per cent.
The present recession will have reduced that proportion further. Indeed,
most local predictions suggest that unemployment will continue rising at
least until well into the second half of this year and possibly into 1993.
Given the cyclical nature of the engineering industry, broadly defined, the
process of reducing dependence on manufacturing may provide a greater degree
of employment stability. But there are two problems.
The first is that, as a generalisation, jobs with wage rates which
traditionally had supported a family have disappeared to be replaced by
service sector jobs which offer less money. Labour surveys have shown that
the likely maximum wage for office staff is about the median level for
industrial earnings. They have also shown that, although basic pay for
full-time working women is roughly two-thirds of the level of male pay, it
is double the level paid to part time working women.
The second problem is that the decline of the manufacturing sector and the
rise of the services sector gives rise to a mismatch of skills. Service
sector employers do not need people with expertise in industrial working.
Given continued expansion of the Coventry services sector, finding new
entrants to the labour force will assume a greater importance even as jobs
are being lost.
The pattern for employment trends has been set. Dr Michael Healey, principal
lecturer in geography at Coventry Polytechnic, believes that, in terms of
job creation in the city, three factors are likely to be evident over the
coming years: there will be more part-time working, more flexible employment
practices and, as the present jobless statistics have foreshadowed, there
will be an even greater role for women.
 ----------------------------------------
