<DATE>920529
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAY 92 / Survey of Coventry (2): A changing economic base -
Manufacturing employment is concentrated in a small number of large
companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAFEWAY has a new supermarket on one of the western approaches to Coventry
city centre. Nearby, a bridge with the name Alvis painted on it, spans the
road. It is a natural historic juxtaposition, symbolic of changes in the
city's economy, writes Paul Cheeseright.
Alvis, the fighting vehicle manufacturer, owned the land where Safeway now
operates, but it has slimmed down and moved out of the city centre: where
once there was industry, there are services, a switch which is the single
most important characteristic of the Coventry economy since the recession of
the early 1980s.
Retrospectively, it is clear that manufacturing peaked in 1966, but the
critical years were between 1974 and 1982. 'During that period, Coventry
lost 46 per cent of its manufacturing jobs - 53,000. A major shift took
place in the local economy,' says Mr Michael Healey, principal lecturer in
geography at Coventry Polytechnic and the author of numerous studies on
Coventry's economic development.
His research showed that nearly two thirds of the manufacturing job losses
were caused by recession and changes in the industrial structure  -
'Coventry suffered from the weakness of the national economy,' Mr Healey
noted. Yet, despite the relative decline of manufacturing, the economic
significance of industry remains huge, and the 1990s recession may also lead
to permanent losses of capacity.
Indeed, there are local fears - and Coventry is not unique in this respect -
that the scale of the cutbacks, the reduced level of training, and financial
difficulties in coping with any expansion in demand will mean that companies
may not be able to respond quickly to an upturn in orders.
Certainly skill shortages are expected to recur. This may be unduly
pessimistic if only because the manufacturing base is held together now, as
it was 20 years ago, by a relatively small number of companies. The 100
largest employers account for around 60 per cent of total employment in the
city and within that 100, the top 15 account for around 45 per cent. These
are not the sort of companies that necessarily have trouble with the bank
manager.
The three largest private sector employers are Jaguar, GPT and Peugeot
Talbot, but the largest employer of all is Coventry City Council.
Employment is highly concentrated, and in manufacturing is spread over a
narrow range of sectors, primarily metal goods and engineering, with a
particular emphasis on vehicle manufacture: the historic industrial base
remains intact.
WITH more than half of its jobs in manufacturing now in the control of
companies headquartered outside the region, and frequently abroad, the
Coventry economy has, however, been prey to global economic movement. There
has not until recently been the leavening and diversity provided by local
small companies. Nor indeed has there been the stability which comes from
such diversity.
But the shockwaves of the 1980s recession, the easy credit of the mid-1980s
and a changing appreciation insouth-east England of Coventry's role in the
national economy has set off change. Reli ance on a small range of
manufacturers and a narrow range of products is diminishing.
On the basis of information gleaned from VAT registrations, Coventry had,
during the 1980s, an exceptionally high rate of business formation. There
was a growth rate of 41 per cent. This was not only the highest of any
district in the West Midlands but 12 percentage points greater than the
national average.
Surveys suggest both that the vast majority of the new businesses have been
of local origin and in the services sector.
The services sector has been expanded by inward investment. At a time when
the south-east England economy was growing quickly, Coventry was seen as
close enough to be convenient, and cheap enough to be attractive.
Indeed, reports Mr Harvey Williams, regional spokesman for the Royal
Institution of Chartered Surveyors, current office rents in and around
Coventry for new or recently refurbished property are between Pounds 12 and
Pounds 14 a square foot, compared with Pounds 17-18 in Birmingham and Pounds
40 in the south-east.
Yet, Coventry's significance as an office centre should not be overstated -
'a large proportion of service functions have been back-office functions.
'I don't think we would see ourselves as in the position of Birmingham,
saying we want to be some kind of financial services centre,' says Mr Trevor
Cornfoot, the City Council's head of economic development. Coventry is
instead becoming an office dormitory of the south-east.
Many of the new jobs have gone to business parks on the periphery of the
city, leaving the city council anxious to secure other forms of development
in the centre, through, for example, the expansion of hotel, leisure and
retail facilities.
Yet, come what may, Coventry's future, like that of the West Midlands as a
whole, is indissolubly linked to that of the engineering industry. The
problem has been to secure the growth of companies which will at once
diminish economic dependence on the traditional employers, widen the
industrial base and provide the development opportunities for the technology
of the next generation.
The city council calculates that there are now 300 companies in Coventry
engaged in high technology activities.
One stimulus has been the University of Warwick Science Park, a centre of
research and development for 54 companies of diverse origin - 'the science
park has made a difference to the quality of companies entering the city,'
notes Mr Cornfoot.
In spite of all these changes, Coventry has not managed to compensate, at
least in employment terms, for the de-industrialisation which took place
during the late 1970s and the early 1980s.
Although greater diversity carries the promise of greater stability, it is
not clear, especially after taking into account the effects of the current
recession, that the local economy has reached the stage where a new
generation of growth is assured.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
