FT  28 MAY 92 / International Company News: CIBC sets aside CDollars 1bn to
cover losses on O&amp;Y
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADIAN Imperial Bank of Commerce, the biggest lender to Olympia and York,
has set aside a special provision of CDollars 1bn to cover possible losses
from the debt-burdened property developer.
As a result of this provision, the bank suffered a second-quarter loss of
CDollars 440m (USDollars 370m) or CDollars 2.55 a share, compared with
earnings of CDollars 186m or 90 cents in the three months to April 30 1991.
CIBC said that despite the big second-quarter loss, it was confident of a
profit for fiscal 1992 as a whole, and that it had no plans to cut its
dividend.
The report by CIBC, Canada's second biggest financial institution, is the
first time the bank has discussed its exposure to O&amp;Y. It said that its
total exposure to O&amp;Y is CDollars 860m, somewhat lower than analysts had
estimated. About half of the loans apply to the Canary Wharf project in
London's Docklands, with the rest split between properties in the US and
Canada.
The CDollars 1bn provision covers not only the O&amp;Y exposure, but also an
unidentified troubled account in Australia, and possible further losses due
to the poor business conditions in Canada.
Mr Donald Fullerton, who retires as chairman next week, said the bank
considers the provision to be sufficient to 'cover a wide range of
developments' and 'to put the O&amp;Y problem behind us'.
