<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / International Company News: US phone companies in Dollars
2.85bn merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPRINT, the third largest US long distance telephone company, and Centel, a
large Chicago-based local telephone company, last night announced plans to
merge through an exchange of shares which values Centel at Dollars 2.85bn.
The deal, announced after the New York Stock Exchange closed for the day, is
the latest example of a wave of consolidation sweeping through the US
telecommunications industry.
Centel announced last January that it would consider putting itself up for
sale as part of a review of strategy options. But the nature of last night's
deal, and the price put on the Chicago company, took the market by surprise.
The merger, which is expected to be tax free to shareholders of both
companies, involves the conversion of each share of Centel's common stock
into 1.37 shares of Sprint stock. Sprint's closing price of Dollars 24 1/2
values each Centel share at Dollars 33.56 and the whole company at Dollars
2.85bn. Centel shares closed at Dollars 42 1/2 , up Dollars  3/4 .
The combined group, of which Centel will own 35 per cent, will retain the
Sprint name and will have an asset book value of nearly Dollars 14bn. Mr
William Esrey, Sprint's chairman and chief executive, will retain these
titles while Mr Jack Frazee, chairman of Centel, will become president and
chief operating officer.
Mr Esrey pointed out that the combined company would be the only one in the
US which operated in all three large telecommunications markets.
The three markets are: long distance, which provides Sprint with Dollars
5.5bn of its Dollars 8.8bn annual revenues; local services, where Sprint
serves 4m lines in 17 states and Centel has 1.6m lines in six states, four
of them common to Sprint; and cellular communications, where Centel operates
in more than 40 metropolitan areas and over 50 rural ones.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
