<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / US calls for joint action to control arms sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US administration is proposing the establishment of a multilateral
co-operation council on which its western allies and its former Eastern bloc
adversaries would work jointly to screen sales of sensitive technology to
unstable or outlaw regimes.
The plan was put forward by Mr James Baker, the US secretary of state, in a
letter to the foreign ministers of the 16 other western countries which
belong to the Co-ordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls
(Cocom). It is expected to be discussed at a high-level Cocom meeting in
Paris next Monday and Tuesday.
US concern has veered increasingly towards the need for controls on trade in
weapons, military and 'dual-use' technologies to governments which are
often-hostile like Iraq, Libya and North Korea.
The Gulf conflict, the collapse of the Eastern bloc and the emergence of
former communist governments which are now starved of hard currency,
therefore might be tempted to sell off their surplus weapons, has
intensified US concerns.
Terming his proposal 'a major undertaking', Mr Baker envisages the
co-operation council as a forum to 'engage the central and eastern European
states and the former Soviet Union in a dialogue on the control of sensitive
technologies'.
He added that it would be modelled 'somewhat after Nato's North Atlantic
Co-operation Council'.
Mr Baker said the new council should provide technical assistance for the
establishment of comparable export control regimes in all of the former
Communist countries and to provide a forum for Cocom 'to address new
strategic threats in co-operation with central and eastern Europe and the
new independent states'.
The co-operation council would also ease access to currently controlled
western technologies to the former Soviet bloc countries.
This proposal is bound to be applauded in Europe, where the US is seen as
dragging its feet on export-control liberalisation, particularly for fibre
optics. A US government official yesterday said fibre optics would be one of
the 'issues' to be discussed next week.
'The co-operation council will provide an effective forum for consultation,
collaboration and reform,' Mr Baker said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
