<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / The Cadbury Report: Men behind the decisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Committee on the Financial Aspects of Corporate Governance was
officially formed a year ago at the instigation of the accountancy bodies
and the Stock Exchange.
Mr Michael Lickiss, a partner at Grant Thornton and then chairman of the
Institute of Chartered Accountants, Sir Ron Dearing, chairman of the
Financial Reporting Council, and Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, Stock Exchange
chairman, were its founding members.
After discussions with the government, a committee with representatives from
industry, shareholder groups and the accountancy profession was formed under
the chairmanship of Sir Adrian Cadbury. Other members were:
Mr Ian Butler, a member of the CBI Council. Mr Jim Butler, senior partner,
KPMG Peat Marwick.
Mr Jonathan Charkham, adviser to the Governor of the Bank of England.
Mr Hugh Collum, chairman, 100 Group of Finance Directors, and finance
director at SmithKline Beecham.
Mr Andrew Likierman, Professor of Accounting and Financial Control, London
Business School.
Mr Nigel Macdonald, vice-president, Institute of Chartered Accountants of
Scotland. Mr Mike Sandland, chairman, Institutional Shareholders Committee.
Mr Mark Sheldon, vice-president, Law Society.
Sir Dermot de Trafford, IoD chairman.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                  MAIN POINTS OF CADBURY REPORT
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies must disclose extent of compliance with Cadbury code to
maintain a stock exchange listing
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Board authority divided between chairman and chief executive.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Pay packages of chairman and highest-paid UK director should be
disclosed in annual accounts split into salary and performance-related
pay
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Each board should have an adult committee 'wholly or mainly' composed
of non-executives
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Interim financial statements should be discussed with auditors although
they need not be formally audited.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Audit committees should meet at least once a year with external auditors
and without the presence of executive directors.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
