<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / The Cadbury Report: Labour attacks voluntary approach
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE REPORT was greeted with some disappointment by Ms Marjorie Mowlam, who
speaks for Labour on corporate affairs, but it was welcomed by ministers.
Ms Mowlam questioned the efficacy of peer group pressure as a way of
enforcing the code of practice and warned that the use of a voluntary code
might amount to a 'recipe for inactivity'.
She said: 'We have had best-practice codes before - from the Association of
British Insurers and from the Institutional Shareholders Committee. I am not
sure they ever go far enough.'
She highlighted areas where she believed the report should have gone
further, commenting on its 'rather vague' reference to companies finding new
ways of working with shareholders. She said that it could have proposed
simplified annual reports or training for shareholders.
A further weakness was the report's comments on the role of non-executive
directors because they did not address where they might be found and whether
they should be trained.
Ms Mowlam also commented that, if the report were serious in addressing the
issue of boardroom pay, it would have recommended that annual meetings
should be able to vote on directors' salaries.
She was disappointed the report did not offer fundamental change, and warned
that as business activity recovered in the 1990s, the same drawbacks would
re-emerge.
'Practical guidelines should have been laid down,' she said.
She welcomed some elements in the document, such as the proposed extension
of statutory protection for auditors reporting reasonable suspicion of
fraud.
Mr Neil Hamilton, the corporate affairs minister, said the report was a
valuable contribution to the debate on improving corporate governance. In
particular, he applauded the idea of a voluntary code of practice, hailing
it as 'an important step forward in improving corporate governance'.
The Department of Trade and Industry emphasised that the report was a draft.
The government would look again at it in the light of the comments it
attracted.
</TEXT>
