<PROFILE>_AN-CE1BHAEHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920528
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Economists predict growth will remain weak: Conservative
election victory fails to brighten forecasts - National Institute says
government expectations may not be met
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and CHRISTOPHER FLOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC growth in the UK will continue to crawl along at a weak level for
the rest of this year and next, according to the latest Financial Times
survey of forecasts on the UK economy.
In spite of the Conservative party's election victory in April and a
supposed renewal of confidence, economists have scarcely altered their
growth forecasts since the election.
Economists expect gross domestic product to grow 0.8 per cent this year.
Even next year, GDP growth will not quite recover to the so-called 'trend'
rate of about 2.5 per cent - the level at which the economy is thought to be
able to grow without stretching productive capacity and provoking inflation.
Forecasters project that growth will hover at about 2.4 per cent next year.
The consensus from economists at 22 universities, intergovernmental
institutions, independent think-tanks and City investment houses is that
unemployment will continue to grow over the next two years, rising to 2.75m
by the end of this year and to just under 3m by the end of next. Eight of
the economists surveyed forecast that the number of jobless would reach 3m
next year.
Most are confident that the continued pressure on employment will bring down
average earnings growth to below 7 per cent and reduce unit-wage-cost
inflation.
Projections for output this year are particularly gloomy. The consensus
among the City economists is for output to fall by just less than 1 per
cent. The overall average, at an increase of just under 1 per cent, is only
slightly more cheerful.
Investment is forecast to fall substantially this year but to rebound with
force next year, consensus growth rate of about 4 per cent.
Forecasters do not expect inflation to wither greatly from present levels.
The average forecasts for this year and next, at well over 3 per cent for
both years, are a long way off the Chancellor's desired rate of 2 per cent.
The UK's trade deficit remains a big concern. Nearly all the economists
surveyed predict a worse current-account balance this year than the Pounds
6.5bn deficit projected by the Treasury in the March budget - the consensus
is for a deficit of Pounds 8.4bn - but their forecasts might be too benign
in the light of the most recent current-account data.
Figures for the first four months of this year, released earlier this week,
may be revised substantially in mid June, when more detailed calculations of
the first-quarter 'invisibles' are available.
Goldman Sachs takes the rent-account balance. It predicts a deficit of
Pounds 16.7bn next year, more than twice the size of some of the other
forecasts.
The forecasts for interest rates reflect the continuing constraints of the
UK's membership of the European exchange rate mechanism. The average
forecasts do not suggest that Britain will be able to cut its interest rates
below German rates, although the idea is entertained by some economists.
Mr Giles Keating of Credit Suisse First Boston says: 'I see no problem in UK
interest rates falling below German, although this would be accompanied by
sterling's being a little weaker within the ERM than it is now.'
The gloomiest forecasts come from UBS Phillips and Drew and Professor Wynne
Godley at Cambridge University. Prof Godley is the only economist to
forecast negative GDP growth this year and has the lowest projection for
growth next year. He predicts a PSBR of Pounds 33bn this financial year and
sees unemployment surpassing 3m next year.
UBS sees no growth this year, rising to 1.4 per cent next year.
A much more bullish outlook comes from Mr Michael Knapp at BZW. He forecasts
growth of 1.5 per cent this year and is the only economist to forecast that
unemployment will fall next year.
Mr Richard Jeffrey at Charterhouse Tilney believes that the bottom of the
economic cycle was in the middle of the last year, with a pause before the
election. 'I think the recovery will surprise people by its strength,' he
says.
Since the last FT compilation of forecasts in January, Hoare Govett is no
longer included in the panel and Charterhouse Tilney and Yamaichi have been
added.
The OECD forecast has been included as a memorandum item only because it
dates from last December and is therefore out of date. The OECD secretariat
has prepared a new UK forecast but refuses to release it until the
publication of the next OECD Economic Outlook at the end of June, by which
time it will also be out of date.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
