FT  28 MAY 92 / Sales optimism reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPTIMISM about sales among small businesses has risen markedly in the past
three months, according to the latest NatWest Quarterly Survey of Small
Business.
A rise in sales is expected by 20 per cent more small business owners in the
present quarter - April to June - than expect sales to fall. In the previous
survey, 10 per cent more businesses expected sales to fall.
Ms Jane Bradford, head of small-business services, said: 'The position is
better than at any time since early 1991, suggesting the bottom of the cycle
has passed.'
Such optimism contrasted with actual sales performance, with 4 per cent more
businesses reporting lower sales, unchanged on the percentage for the
previous quarter.
Most businesses still expect to reduce employment levels and cut investments
in the present quarter, but the percentages involved are smaller.
On balance, 4 per cent more businesses expect to cut jobs compared with 17
per cent in the previous quarter, while 6 per cent will cut investment
compared with 14 per cent.
</TEXT>
