<PROFILE>_AN-CE1BHAEFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920528
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / EC budget increase is urged for EMU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community needs a much larger budget to make a success of
economic and monetary union, according to Sir Donald MacDougall, a former
chief economic adviser to the UK government.
Writing in the National Institute Economic Review, Sir Donald said countries
might face 'a prolonged period of painful adjustment, with sluggish or even
negative economic growth' if they did not have Community financial help
after losing the power to vary exchange rates.
Sir Donald, appointed by the EC Commission in the late 1970s to head a
high-level study group on public finance and European integration, said the
lack of a larger budget 'would run the risk of setting back, rather than
promoting, progress towards closer integration in Europe'.
His 1977 report advocated increasing the EC budget from the then 0.7 per
cent of Community GDP to between 2 and 2.5 per cent over a decade.
</TEXT>
