<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Council watchdog urges rise in homes for rent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT action is needed to remedy the shortfall in affordable housing
for rent, according to a report published today by the Audit Commission.
The local-government watchdog warns that there will be a growing shortfall
in rentable properties at reasonable cost in the next few years.
Ms Sheila McKechnie, director of the housing charity Shelter, said: 'We want
the government to look again at the implications of the projected Pounds 1bn
reduction in local-authority housing resources.'
The Audit Commission's report, she said, 'reinforces Shelter's call for
extra affordable homes as the only way to stop spiralling homelessness'.
The commission says councils could do more to meet the demand for social
housing from their existing resources, but that would still not eliminate
the shortfall.
Its report estimates that an additional 74,000 homes will be needed every
year for the next 10 years to meet the demand.
The commission is also critical of the government's encouragement of
large-scale transfers of council homes to housing associations. It notes
that such transfers have resulted in increased rents and more government
costs in higher housing benefit.
The government has promised housing associations sufficient finance to build
57,000 homes a year by 1994-95. But with local authorities expected to build
only another 5,000 homes a year, there would still be a shortfall.
Sir George Young, the housing minister, said the government supported the
commission's recommendations on measures local authorities could take. He
added that ministers were looking at a range of initiatives to bridge the
housing gap. They included the use of the planning system to increase the
supply of affordable housing, and - through housing associations - reducing
the risks of letting for private landlords.
Sir George did not dispute the Pounds 1bn figure for the reduction in
local-authority housing resources, but pointed to increases in the budget
for the Housing Corporation. 'We don't expect local authorities to build new
family homes for rent,' he said.
The commission says that the gap could be partly closed if local authorities
made better use of their existing housing stock. It suggests that:
Gaps between lettings are still unnecessarily long. Achieving the
commission's target of three weeks (six weeks in London) would create 26,000
extra lettings and generate additional rents.
Reducing the growing number of unlicensed tenancies would provide 7,000 new
homes (mostly in London).
Many councils fail to use their full entitlement to nominate tenants to
registered housing associations. Councils could do more to encourage people
to move into more suitable council homes - perhaps by increasing rent
differentials so that people in unnecessarily large homes were encouraged to
move.
The report estimates that the backlog of maintenance and repairs to
local-authority housing stock has fallen to about Pounds 8.5bn (down from
Pounds 11bn in 1985). While the number of homes in the private sector
lacking basic amenities has continued to fall, the level of homes in serious
disrepair or unfit is stable.
Developing Local Housing. Audit Commission. HMSO. Pounds 12.
</TEXT>
