<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Obituary of Peter Jenkins: Leading political journalist
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
PETER Jenkins, who died yesterday at the age of 58, was one of the most
accomplished British political journalists and one who was equally at home
writing about foreign affairs.
Although he spent the last five years as associate editor and political
columnist at The Independent, and was initiated into national journalism by
two years at the Financial Times, it is probably for his long spell at The
Guardian that he will be most remembered.
Jenkins made his breakthrough at The Guardian as labour correspondent during
the first years of Harold Wilson's premiership - a time when industrial
disputes and trade union law topped the political agenda. He went on to
become the paper's Washington columnist.
When he returned to London as political commentator and policy editor in
1974, he watched the decline of the Labour party and the rise of
Thatcherism. The latter did not attract him and he was saddened by the
Labour government's failure to tame the excesses of the unions.
Jenkins's political sympathies were with the Social Democrats and he
recorded with pleasure the emergence of the SDP in 1981. He saw himself as
part of the political process, helping the politicians and the public to
communicate with each other. His book, Mrs Thatcher's Revolution, published
in 1987, concluded that it was only 'half a revolution', which perhaps seems
a more accurate judgment now than it did then.
Jenkins moved briefly to The Sunday Times in 1985, but the paper's style did
not suit him and he settled at The Independent two years later. Some of his
best columns appeared only recently, when he assessed the current state of
Germany, a country he had always followed closely. He was a member of the
Konigswinter conference, which fosters Anglo-German relations.
Outside politics and journalism, one of his chief interests was theatre.
Jenkins had one child with his first wife, Charlotte. In 1970 he married the
journalist Polly Toynbee, with whom he had three children.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-5856</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE1BHADYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920528
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Obituary of Lord McFadzean: Free marketeer
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD McFadzean of Kelvinside, who has died aged 76, was chairman in
succession of Shell, British Airways and Rolls-Royce in the 1970s and 1980s.
An outspoken, stocky Scot, he combined a career as an industrialist with an
intellectual commitment to free-market economics. As a visiting professor of
economics at Strathclyde University from 1967 to 1976 he attacked the
theories of John Kenneth Galbraith.
When Margaret Thatcher came to power in 1979 he described her as 'the most
intelligent person I have ever met'.
He was born in Glasgow on November 26 1915 and ran away to sea at the age of
14, returning a year later. He trained as an economist, gaining a
first-class degree at Glasgow University, then studying at the London School
of Economics.
In 1938 he joined the Board of Trade and moved quickly on to the Treasury.
After the Second World War he worked for the Malayan government and the
Colonial Development Corporation.
At 36, McFadzean entered the private sector with Shell. Within nine years,
his uncompromising approach to efficiency earned him a place on the board
and his outspokenness the sobriquet 'Fearless Frank'. In 1972 he became
chairman of Shell.
In 1976 he was one of the few industrialists prepared to take on the running
of the then state-owned British Airways. He instituted job cuts and clashed
with the unions. Sir Keith Joseph asked him to write a pamphlet which was
published under the title The Economics of John Kenneth Galbraith: a Study
in Fantasy.
After the 1979 Conservative victory, he moved to Rolls-Royce, which he led
through the recession of 1981-83, shedding 20,000 jobs and turning a Pounds
22m loss in 1980 into an Pounds 18m profit in 1981.
He was chairman of the Trade Policy Research Centre from 1971 until 1982. He
was knighted in 1975 and created a life peer as Baron McFadzean of
Kelvinside in 1980.
He married Isabel Beattie in 1938. Their daughter, Felicity, married Baron
Marsh, the former Labour transport minister. Isabel died in 1987 and he
married Sonja Khung in 1988.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-5857</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CE1BHADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920528
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Pay offer of 3.8% for council staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL GOVERNMENT white-collar workers may receive one of the lowest pay
settlements in the public sector this year after employers yesterday offered
a 3.8 per cent rise in basic pay.
The offer, up from a previous 3.6 per cent, was dismissed by Nalgo, the main
union in the negotiations, as unrealistically low. Mr Dennis Reed, Nalgo
local-government officer, said he hoped for a negotiated settlement but
added that industrial action was possible.
The talks cover about 750,000 workers and set the tone for negotiations for
1m manual workers in local government who traditionally receive a similar
rise.
The offer compares with proposed settlements for the majority of Britain's
civil servants of between 4.5 per cent and 4.75 per cent including
performance-related pay provisions. Some health workers have been offered
more.
Council associations are to consult authorities on their opinions on a
settlement. However, Mr Steve Bubb, assistant secretary at the Association
of Metropolitan Authorities, said there would be no dramatic movement.
The revenue support grant allowance for inflation was 4.8 per cent but
authorities argue that there is less than that available for white-collar
workers. That is in part because of a 7.5 per cent rise for teachers which
was determined by a pay review body.
</TEXT>
