<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Labour moves to end union role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Labour leadership agreed yesterday to call on its policymaking annual
conference to end the trade unions' role in the selection of parliamentary
candidates.
But Mr Neil Kinnock, who had proposed the changeover to a simple one member,
one vote system, used his first interviews since the general election to
insist that there was no question of severing the unions' historic links
with the party.
Without union support for Labour the Conservatives would have had 'a near
monopoly' of the press, political funding and power, the party leader told
the national executive committee. 'I don't believe there is anyone in
Britain who believes that British democracy would have been best served in
that fashion,' he said. His warning came as officials confirmed that
individual membership of the party had fallen to 260,000 from 320,000 in
1990.
This is the lowest figure for 60 years and another compelling reason for
maintaining union financial support.
NEC members voted by 20 to 2 against to support the rule change with just Mr
Tony Benn and Mr Dennis Skinner, the veteran leftwingers dissenting.
By a similar margin, they went on to approve a proposal for Mr Larry Whitty,
the general secretary, to hold consultations on a wide ranging review of the
party's relationship with the unions, reporting back to the executive next
month.
That proposal, tabled by Mr Tom Sawyer, an NEC member and deputy general
secretary of the public service union NUPE, comes as a deliberate effort to
calm the debate on the link that has raged since criticism of union
influence surfaced with the party's leadership election. Union leaders, who
provide the overwhelming bulk of Labour's funding, have been growing
increasingly angry at the attacks.
Mr Whitty will now seek opinions on how to review the unions' role in the
leadership election - currently they command 40 per cent of the electoral
college - their affiliation fees and representation on the national
executive and the soon to be established national policy forum.
Also high on the agenda will be the controversial block vote at conference,
whereby union delegations control some 90 per cent of the votes. At
Blackpool this autumn, delegates will vote on a proposal to reduce the union
weighting against the constituency parties to 70-30.
</TEXT>
