FT  28 MAY 92 / International Company News: Italians may buy Del Monte Foods
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN and NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS are under way for the sale of Del Monte Foods, the US tinned
foods group formerly part of RJR Nabisco, to Cragnotti &amp; Partners Capital
Investment (C&amp;P), the Italian financial concern trying to create a new
international operation in the foods sector.
Some industry sources said a preliminary agreement could be ready for
signing next month but others suggested that the deal was not so advanced.
A Dollars 300m price tag was put on Del Monte in an Italian newspaper report
yesterday but the full price, including assumption of debt, seems likely to
be significantly higher if a deal goes ahead.
Under the broad outlines of the deal, confirmed by C&amp;P yesterday, the
Italian company would take control of Del Monte through the transfer of its
recently-acquired Cica tinned foods subsidiary in Brazil, as well as the
purchase of a direct stake. Part of the enlarged Del Monte group would then
be floated in the US.
Del Monte Foods was created in 1988 after the leveraged buy-out of RJR
Nabisco by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, the US buy-out specialists, as one of
four divisions of the original Del Monte company, which had been acquired in
1978 by R. J. Reynolds.
In 1990, Del Monte Foods, based in California, went through a further change
of ownership after a Dollars 1.54bn Merrill Lynch-backed management buy-out.
Since then, further disposals have taken place. However, sales for the San
Francisco-based business amounted to Dollars 1.4bn last year.
C&amp;P denied that a planned L250bn (Dollars 206m) bond issue was also destined
to finance the transaction. The Italian company, headed by Mr Sergio
Cragnotti, a former chief executive of the Ferruzzi group, was set up in
early 1991 with L450bn in launch capital. Its aim is to establish three
international areas of operation in the foods, detergents and packaging
sectors.
Acquisitions so far have concentrated on packaging. In March 1991, it took a
majority stake in Lawson Mardon, the Canadian packaging group, and six
months later bought 50 per cent of the Ja-Mont paper joint venture.
The purchase of Cica late last year was its first venture on the foods side.
C&amp;P has been negotiating with Del Monte's management and owners for some
months, and is now thought to be the only company in the running to buy the
company, which is now owned by a consortium including management and Merrill
Lynch, the US investment bank.
</TEXT>
