<TEXT>
FLEXTECH is leaving the oil business which carried it to the USM just nine
years ago in favour of children's television.
The company yesterday announced a Pounds 55.3m management buy-out of Expro,
its Aberdeen-based oil services subsidiary.
Shareholders will get a piece of the action through a complicated deal which
allows Flextech to pay Pounds 41.6m - amounting to 120p per share - in place
of a dividend.
The agreement is structured so shareholders, rather than the company, will
pay tax on the sum.
Mr Roger Luard, Flextech director, said the company would retain Pounds 14m
of the proceeds to pay off debt and fund development of media interests. The
main holding, an indirect 50.1 per cent stake in The Children's Channel,
showed losses of Pounds 3m last year.
Mr Luard said Flextech intended to concentrate on the opportunities for
children's and family programming in the growing satellite and cable
markets. By 1995 in the UK alone, he said, it was estimated that there would
be between 8m and 9m cable subscribers, compared with just 500,000 this
year.
The Expro purchase was backed by CINVen, the venture capital group.
