   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR RALPH Robins, Rolls-Royce chief executive, is to succeed Lord Tombs at
the end of September as executive chairman of the UK aero-engine and
industrial power group.
The announcement at the company's annual meeting was overshadowed by bitter
interventions from former employees and shareholders over the group's
handling of its voluntary redundancy scheme.
Lord Tombs, 68, also said Mr Terry Harrison, head of the company's
industrial power activities and former chairman of Northern Engineering
Industries (NEI) which Rolls-Royce took over in 1989, will become the new
chief executive. Sir Ralph, who has spent his entire working life with the
company, had long been regarded as the natural successor to Lord Tombs.
But company directors faced embarrassment yesterday when small shareholders
at the meeting voted against a resolution to enable directors to amend the
company's executive share option scheme. The proposal, to allow the granting
of options at a price 15 per cent below the current market value of
Rolls-Royce shares, will now be put to a ballot.
The vote against the share option scheme reflected the feeling among many
former employees and shareholders over the redundancy scheme and the
company's approach to job cuts.
Rolls-Royce cut about 5,000 jobs last year and has announced a further 3,000
job reductions this year to reduce costs and counter the slowdown in the
commercial engine market and the decline in military business.
Employees, who accepted the company's initial voluntary redundancy package
last year, said they had lost out because Rolls-Royce introduced a more
attractive package last July.
Sir Ralph acknowledged the reaction on the job issue yesterday had been
stronger than expected but said the company had to cope with the reduction
in defence business and the short-term problems in the competitive civil
engine sector.
He also said most Rolls-Royce directors have not had a pay increase for the
past 18 months. Lord Tombs took a pay cut to Pounds 156,000 last year from
Pounds 180,000 the year before.
Lord Tombs is stepping down after seven years as chairman during which he
successfully piloted the company through privatisation in 1987, expanded the
range and market share of its commercial aero-engine business, and
negotiated the merger with NEI.
</TEXT>
