<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Judging from Max Loppert's recent review on this page we should all be sure
to switch on Radio 3 at 7.05 for the live relay from Cardiff of the Welsh
National Opera's new production of Iphigenie en Tauride. The story, taken
from Euripides by Francois Guillard, is that of Iphigenie, daughter of
Agamemnon, and her brother Orestes, in the aftermath of the Trojan war. The
opera was written by Gluck when he was 65 and Kobbe tells the story of a
contemporary who remarked that there were many fine passages in it. 'There
is only one' said the Abbe Arnaud. 'Which?'  - 'The entire work'. In this
production Iphigenie is sung by Diana Montague and Orestes by Simon
Keenlyside.
Two television programmes look at wholesale and retail trade. Business
Matters returns to BBC2 with a documentary about Levi Strauss, the original
manufacturer of denim jeans and now the world's largest clothing company,
which faces a serious problem from counterfeiters (7.25). Channel 4's series
The Black Bag (8.00) looks into allegations that wholesalers of newspapers
and magazines are refusing to supply Asian shopkeepers.
</TEXT>
