FT  28 MAY 92 / Plan on late debts backed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 20 trade associations and small business groups have expressed an
interest in a plan to develop pilot schemes to tackle late payment of debt,
the Department of Trade and Industry said yesterday.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, announced in his March Budget that the
government would provide up to Pounds 90,000 for three trade organisations
to run one-year pilot schemes such as late-payment 'hotlines' for their
members.
Trade associations have until June 15 to submit detailed proposals for
schemes, said Baroness Denton, minister for small businesses.
Initial interest has come from trade bodies representing the building
industry, printing, paint manufacturers, electrical contractors and computer
services. Three other groups, the Federation of Small Businesses, the Forum
of Private Business and the Confederation of British Industry's smaller
firms council, have also backed the idea.
Lady Denton said: 'Trade associations are often the first port of call for
small firms because they understand the nature of their business and its
market. Some are already working on payment issues but we want to expand
their number and the range of support they offer.'
