<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Vocational tests body comes under attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEAD of the Business and Technology Education Council, Britain's largest
provider of vocational qualifications, yesterday launched a strong attack on
the quango responsible for carrying out government policies to promote
work-oriented education.
Mr Parry Rogers, Btec's chairman, condemned the National Council for
Vocational Qualifications as a 'prescriptive regulator' undermining the
quality of courses by over-regulation of their content and standard.
The NCVQ, under the leadership of Sir Bryan Nicholson, chairman of the Post
Office, has been charged by the government with simplifying and
co-ordinating the range of vocational qualifications on offer. It has a
power of validation - which gives it authority over the three main providers
of courses, as government funding for trainees is to be closely tied to
validated courses.
The NCVQ also has the task of ensuring that 80 per cent of the workforce is
covered by national vocational qualifications by the end of this year, and
of overseeing the introduction of the 'general vocational qualifications' -
intended to be work-oriented alternatives to A-levels in England and Wales -
announced in last year's white paper on education and training.
Tension between Btec and the NCVQ has been rising for some time, as the
design and validation process has proceeded. Btec's concern is not limited
to regulation: it is also thought to be worried about the speed of the
introduction of the GVQs - due to be piloted this autumn, and to be
generally available from autumn 1993.
Speaking at the launch of Btec's annual report yesterday, Mr Rogers likened
the NCVQ's approach to 'laying down the minimum specification for a car and
forbidding the manufacturer from offering a higher specification'.
He added: 'That attitude is daft in any circumstances; how much dafter when
done in the name of a government dedicated to market forces]'
Underlying the dispute are differences about the philosophy underlying
vocational courses. The NCVQ wishes to use courses to promote skill-based
training by employers, while Btec is anxious not to sacrifice the broader
educational role of courses.
Mr Rogers emphasised yesterday: 'I for one am unwilling to see Btec students
lose the chance to go on to degree courses where this is what the individual
wants and deserves.'
Concern that standards are at risk and that the NCVQ is adopting an
excessively competence-based approach is voiced far beyond Btec.
An oft-cited example of the trend is the newly validated Btec first diploma
in business and finance, claiming parity of esteem with GCSE, which
comprises competence tests such as filing 20 consecutive documents correctly
and answering 10 telephone calls accurately.
</TEXT>
