FT  28 MAY 92 / World Trade News: US and EC in fresh move to end farm
subsidy row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US AND EC officials met in Washington yesterday to try to end their farm
subsidy impasse that has blocked a 108-nation effort to reform the world's
trading system, Reuter reports from Washington.
EC members last week agreed to reform their farm policy by cutting
government payments to farmers, but the US said there also had to be cuts in
government export subsidies and fewer curbs on food imports.
A US official acknowledged the importance of the cuts in internal subsidies,
but said: 'We're anxious to see if there can be progress on export subsidies
and market access'.
EC refusal to agree to deep cuts in farm subsidies, as demanded by the US
and other food exporters, has hampered progress towards an overall Gatt
accord. Mr Frans Andriessen, EC external relations commissioner, was
yesterday pressing the case that the EC had been flexible on subsidies and
it was now the US's turn.
Mr Andriessen yesterday met US Secretary of State James Baker, Mr Edward
Madigan, agriculture secretary, and Mrs Carla Hills, US trade
representative. A US official said a further meeting might be scheduled for
today if warranted.
Mr Arthur Dunkel, Gatt director-general, said on Monday that time was
running out for meeting a December deadline to wind up the talks
successfully.
