<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / World Trade News: Canadian grain for Russia hit by cash
shortage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADIAN grain exports to Russia have slowed to a trickle because of
Moscow's inability to pay foreign shipowners and a ban imposed by Ottawa on
many Russian-owned vessels to counter an infestation of leaf-eating moths.
Russia's shortage of hard currency has already caused Canadian authorities
to impound at least one fully-laden vessel, and appears to be discouraging
other owners from sending ships to Canadian ports.
The slowdown in shipments to Canada's biggest grain export market has also
caused a domestic transport crisis. About half the grain freighters plying
the Great Lakes are at present idle, and several hundred crew members and
grain handlers have been laid off.
The Canadian Grain Transportation Agency (GTA), which co-ordinates
deliveries to the ports, yesterday cut its estimate of June exports. Total
shipments through the Great Lakes port of Thunder Bay are now projected at
0.5m tonnes, half the volume expected a month ago. The GTA has cut its
projection of export volumes through west coast ports from 1.7m tonnes to
1.36m tonnes. Canada exported a total 7.2m tonnes of wheat and 1.2m tonnes
of barley to the former Soviet Union in the season which ended last July.
Although Canada has extended a CDollars 1.5bn (Pounds 714m) line of credit
to Russia for wheat purchases, this does not cover shipping costs. A
spokesman for the Canadian Wheat Board said yesterday that Russia's
inability to pay for foreign-owned vessels appears to be the main problem.
Use of Russian ships is limited by a Canadian government order banning
vessels in port in the Russian Far East during the Asian gypsy-moth spawning
season. The moths, voracious foliage eaters, are a threat to west coast
forests in the US and Canada. An official with Morlines Maritime Agency,
which handles the bulk of wheat shipments to Russia, said that Export Khleb,
the Russian grain-purchasing agency, has not chartered any vessels to load
in a Canadian port before June 3.
</TEXT>
