<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 92 / Outlook for UK jobless bleak for two years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OUTLOOK for Britain's unemployed looks bleak over the next two years
because growth will be too weak to stop the number of people out of work
climbing towards 3m.
Moreover, the latest Financial Times survey of forecasts of the UK economy
suggests inflation will stay stubbornly above the chancellor of the
exchequer's goal of 2 per cent in spite of below-trend growth and a rising
jobless total.
The FT has polled 22 groups of economists at universities, independent
think-tanks and City investment houses. The survey suggests the Treasury's
March prediction of a 1 per cent rise in gross domestic product this year
and 3 per cent in the first half of 1993 is slightly too optimistic.
Instead the average forecast for output growth is about 0.8 per cent this
year and 2.4 per cent in 1993 with unemployment likely to reach 2.9m by the
end of 1993.
Looking further ahead, the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research yesterday cast doubt on the Treasury's medium-term projections that
GDP will grow by 3.5 per cent a year over the fiscal years 1994-95 to
1996-97. In a separate report, it projected no significant drop in UK
unemployment below 2.7m before the end of the decade.
The National Institute lays much of the blame for future slow growth on
'excessive' real interest rates in Europe.
Details, Page 10
</TEXT>
